				 Bharat Shell stake sale okayed
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, Nov. 30: The Union cabinet has approved the sale of Bharat Petroleum Corporation Ltds (BPCL) 49 per cent stake in lubricant marketing firm Bharat Shell Ltd to multinational Shell for Rs 152.40 crore. 																								Shell already holds 51 per cent in Bharat Shell, set up in 1993 to market Shells lubricants in the country. 																								BPCL is leaving the venture as it has developed a competing product.																								Bharat Shell suffered losses till 2001-02, but showed signs of a turnaround after hiving off its loss-making LPG business. The company posted a net profit of Rs 12.12 crore in 2006-07.																								Apart from paying BPCL in cash, Shell will also take over the state-run firms share of the debt run up by Bharat Shell.																								Pollution check																								The Centre has sanctioned a revised amount of Rs 135.44 crore to set up a common effluent treatment plant in Bengal. The plant will reduce pollution in the river Ganga. 																								To be set up at the Calcutta Leather Complex in Bantala, the plant is a part of Ganga Action Plan Phase II under the environment and forest ministrys National River Conservation Plan.																								The Centre and the state government will share the cost equally.																								The government decided to revise the cost estimates for the project at a meeting of the Cabinet Committee on Economic Affairs (CCEA) yesterday. The CCEA had initially approved Rs 65 crore for the plant in 1995.																								About 30 million litres of waste per day from more than 500 tanneries will be treated at the plant.																								The project is expected to be completed by March 2010.																								SCI plans																								The cabinet also allowed the Shipping Corporation of India to buy six carriers at an estimated cost of $269.4 million (Rs 1,077.6 crore) to replace some of its old cargo ships.																								It has also approved deepening a channel at Orissas Paradip Port at a revised cost estimate of Rs 253.359 crore.																								Permission was granted to the Central Board of Excise and Customs for its Rs 600-crore computerisation programme. 
